      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my psych dissertation and i'm stuck on a weird result. my effect size is actually pretty large, but my p-value is 0.06. people keep telling me it's \"not significant\" but it feels like there's a real trend here. can you help me understand the technical reasoning behind why 0.06 is rejected in standard testing even if the data looks like it's moving in the right direction? also how do i explain the \"noise\" that might be causing this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, when the standard threshold is $\\alpha = 0.05$, is indeed just shy of the cutoff, which is why the standard statistical machinery treats it as \"not significant.\" The p-value is essentially the probability of observing your data (or more extreme data) *if the null hypothesis were actually true*. When you get 0.06, it means there's a 6% chance you'd see this result just by random chance, even if nothing is happening.\n\nThat 6% is enough for the strict, traditional testing framework to say, \"Hold on, that's not strong enough evidence to overturn the assumption that nothing is going on.\" The statistical \"noise\"—that's where the real problem lies, and it's usually a combination of sample size, variance, and the inherent messiness of the world. Think of it like trying to find a single, perfect, sharp-edged piece of iron in a pile of rusty scrap metal. You might see a promising shape, but the surrounding junk—the random fluctuations—is too loud to definitively say it's the *real* thing.\n\nIf your effect size is large, that",
      "source": "target",
